editorialSummary.text: Olympic weightlifting instruction offered in a strength-training facility with an industrial vibe.

originalText.text:
I have been a member for three months, and been lifting seriously for about a decade. I strongly recommend JDI Harlem.

If you're expecting a spa, JDI Harlem gives a rough initial impression, but if you want to train, it's a playground.

It has everything you need where it counts for solid strength training: fantastic programming in the app, coaching hours where you can get constructive critique on your lifts, and a community that shares a strong drive for self improvement.

For intermediate/advanced lifters, there is programming that will challenge you in the app and all the necessary equipment to execute.

For beginner lifters, there are coaches around during coaching hours to make sure you're lifting safely and give you technical critique, BUT they split their time between individual clients and the two JDI locations so if you want a specific coach you should speak with them about scheduling or consider getting a session yourself.

If you want to train strength or get into olympic lifting, JDI Harlem is your best shot in town.

originalText.text:
JDI is different. JDI makes powerlifters. JDI helps build the confidence that you don't get at a commercial gym. It's a small family, and that's beautiful. I started using the bar because of JDI. I no longer fear heavy weight; I no longer fear the barbell;
I no longer worry about not being able to lift. JDI also has a community of girls who lift and empower each other through friendship and every lift. Once a month, the Strong Gurls Club gets together and has an event which I look forward to. The best part of my experience is not only am I getting stronger, but my mental health has done a 180, and that's priceless for me. free endorphins!!!!

originalText.text:
STAY AWAY FROM THE HARLEM LOCATION. I really wanted to join this gym, so I went by on my own accord to take a look. I was shocked at the difference between the online reviews and the in person reality.

I visited the Harlem location on an unassuming Saturday afternoon and expected to speak to some of the incredible professionals that everyone here keeps speaking about. I finally found a door with the gym name on it. But something didn’t seem right. The door was riddled with graffiti  and about a foot from the handle was an apparent drug addict who was glitching at random between writhing/tweaking and complete unconsciousness. He looked like he was fighting demons in his mind - and losing.

I still wasn’t sure if I was in the right place, but suddenly a gym goer exited the door - ignoring the poor man to his left as if it was a totally normal occurrence. I walked in to let someone at the front desk know that there was someone potentially overdosing in front of their building. But when I walked in and descended into the basement, I realized that there was no front desk. In fact, when I asked another gym goer - no one who worked at the gym was actually present. It seemed as if anyone could walk into the gym at any time without discretion. The gym was smaller, more crowded and much more poorly lit than the photos here would suggest. The equipment was covered in chalk and looked like it hadn’t been cleaned in a long while. I felt like if I stayed any longer or touched anything, I might get ringworm.

After seeing all the positive reviews here, I thought I must be in the wrong place. I had gotten a really positive referral from a personal trainer friend who recently moved out of the city. I tried to call to set up an appointment for a tour, because I really wanted this gym to work for me. However, no one answered after numerous attempts. So here I am. New in Harlem, still trying to find a decent gym nearby. I couldn’t imagine paying $180 a month to go to the gym here. I suppose the gym has gone steeply downhill since these commenters have been to Harlem. Management is likely making a concerted effort to move their operations to Tribeca, and using the Harlem location as a cash cow before closing it down.

originalText.text: I used to go to this gym a couple years ago before moving away. It is the best strength training gym I’ve gone to and unique in the level of care that the coaches/instructors provide. I felt safe learning to lift at this gym and learning how to safely lift. The coaches treat other people with kindness and empathy. I am thankful for the experience going to JDI Barbell and recommend it to anybody who lives in nyc who wants to learn how to lift or who wants to go to a different gym.
